1) Multiple Eye Disease Detection (Project Explanation)

Problem:
The goal of this project was to help with early detection of eye diseases using AI, because manual diagnosis 
by ophthalmologists can be time-consuming and sometimes prone to human limitations.

Approach:
I used pre-trained CNN models with transfer learning to classify fundus images into four classes: Normal, Cataract, Glaucoma, and 
Diabetic Retinopathy. During preprocessing, I performed background removal and image resizing so that the model 
focuses on important eye features and the images match the input size required by the models. 
I experimented with models such as InceptionV3, MobileNetV2, and EfficientNet.

Result:
Among the tested models, MobileNetV2 performed the best and achieved around 98.5% accuracy.

Impact:
This project shows how deep learning can support early diagnosis of eye diseases, and the 
research was later published in IEEE Xplore

Followup:
2) Why did MobileNetV2 perform better than other models?

MobileNetV2 performed better because it is lightweight and efficient, with fewer parameters compared to other deep models. 
It can capture important features while keeping computational cost low, which helped achieve better accuracy for this dataset.

3) What evaluation metrics did you use?

I evaluated the model using accuracy, precision, recall, and F1-score to measure classification performance and 
ensure the model performs well across all classes.

4) Why did you use a pre-trained model?

I used a pre-trained model with transfer learning because training a deep CNN from scratch requires a very large dataset and 
high computational resources. Pre-trained models are already trained on large datasets like ImageNet and 
have learned general visual features such as edges, shapes, and textures. By fine-tuning the model on my dataset, 
I could achieve better performance with less training time and fewer data samples.

5) What challenges did you face?

One challenge was that fundus images contain a large background area that is not useful for disease detection. 
If this background is not handled properly, the model may treat it as a feature and reduce classification accuracy. 
To address this, I applied background removal and preprocessing techniques, which helped the model focus only on the important 
retinal features

2nd Project: 
6) SQLGenie – Natural Language to SQL Chatbot

Problem:
Many users want to get information from a database but may not know how to write SQL queries.

Approach:
To solve this, I developed SQLGenie, where users can ask questions in natural language. The system uses the 
OpenAI API to convert the user’s question into an SQL query. The generated query is executed on the database, and the 
retrieved result is then presented to the user in a simple natural language format.

Tools:
I implemented this system using Python, OpenAI API, SQL, and Streamlit for the interface.

Impact:
This project makes database interaction easier for users who are not familiar with SQL, 
allowing them to access data using natural language.

7) AWS cloud:
For relational data, a better option is Amazon RDS, because it is designed to manage relational databases such as MySQL, 
PostgreSQL, or MariaDB. It provides features like automated backups, scalability, security, and easy database management, 
which makes it suitable for applications that require SQL queries and structured data.

8) How do you handle incorrect SQL queries generated by the LLM?
A generated query may sometimes be incorrect. To handle this, we can validate the query before execution and 
also provide the database schema in the prompt so the model generates more accurate SQL.

Project
9)Online News Popularity Prediction
Problem

During this project, I worked on predicting the popularity of online news articles. It is difficult for publishers to know in advance whether an article will become popular or not.

Approach

To solve this, I built a machine learning model that predicts whether a news article will be popular based on its features. The dataset included attributes such as number of words, keywords, publishing day, and content-related features.
I performed data preprocessing, feature selection, and exploratory data analysis, and then trained multiple machine learning models to predict the popularity of the news articles.

Tools

I implemented the project using Python, Pandas, NumPy, Scikit-learn, and visualization libraries such as Matplotlib and Seaborn.

Impact

This model can help publishers understand which types of articles are more likely to gain attention, which can help improve content strategy and audience engagement.
